<article>
    <h1>BY THE NUM&#xAD;BERS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201128/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-28"><time>2020-11-28</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Jan Lee</span>
    </section>

    <p>In­ter­net love scam cases in­creased in the first three months of the year, ac­cord­ing to po­lice fig­ures. There were 175 cases recorded be­tween Jan 1 and March 31, up 33.6 per cent from 131 in the same pe­riod last year.</p>
    <p>The money stolen to­talled about</p>
    <p>$6.6 mil­lion, down from about $7.1 mil­lion.</p>
    <p>So­cial me­dia sites Face­book and In­sta­gram were the two most com­mon plat­forms where vic­tims were ap­proached.</p>
    <p>The po­lice urge the pub­lic to be care­ful when be­friend­ing strangers on­line and to be wary when asked to send money to peo­ple they do not know or have not met in per­son be­fore.</p>
    <p>To know more about such scams, the pub­lic can go to sca­malert.sg or call the Anti-Scam Hot­line on 1800-722-6688. Those with in­for­ma­tion on such scams can also con­tact the po­lice on 1800-255-0000 or www.po­lice.gov.sg/iwit­ness.</p>


</article>

